{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"17bc4175-0079-403c-8060-b919b7688e67","content":"No project found at that path, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport:\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command`/`args`** — Uses `dotnet run` to build and launch the project.\n- Your MCP server must read JSON-RPC messages from **stdin** and write responses to **stdout**. Make sure any logging goes to **stderr**, not stdout.\n\nIf you publish a self-contained binary instead, replace the command:\n\n```json\n\"command\": \"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Release/net8.0/MyMcpServer\"\n```\n\nAfter saving, open the **Copilot Chat** panel in agent mode — it will auto-discover the server and list its tools.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"58cf409c-cf2b-45f7-a6ff-31ac6a6aa9f3","outputTokens":309,"requestId":"B025:360FF2:D9AE5C:F65CFB:6A027D70"},"id":"6ace8921-f73c-493e-a333-73ad59ca3656","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:08:07.976Z","parentId":"1339ffd4-5681-4ffa-b023-d9fff29a384d"}
